## 9. Relationship Cardinality
 
**Definition:** Relationship cardinality is the rule that defines **how many instances of one entity can be associated with instances of another entity** in a database.
 
### Types of Cardinality:
 
| Type | Notation | Meaning |
|---|---|---|
| One-to-One | 1:1 | One record in A relates to exactly one record in B |
| One-to-Many | 1:N | One record in A relates to many records in B |
| Many-to-One | N:1 | Many records in A relate to one record in B |
| Many-to-Many | N:N | Many records in A relate to many records in B |
 
### Cardinality Signs (ERD Notation):
 
| Symbol | Meaning |
|---|---|
| `——` (single line) | One |
| `——<` (crow's foot) | Many |
| `——O——` (circle) | Zero or One |
| `——\|<` | One or Many |
| `>——<` | Many to Many |
| `——O<` | Zero or Many |
 
---
 
## 10. Entity-Relationship (ER) Diagram
 
**Definition:** An ER diagram is a diagram that shows entities, their attributes, and the relationships between them.
 
It is the visual blueprint used during database system design to plan the structure before building the actual database.
 
